<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911230-0022</DOCNO><DOCID>911230-0022.</DOCID><HL>   Shearson and Merrill   Agree to Settle Claims   From Tracor Buy-Out</HL><DATE>12/30/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4</SO><CO>   AXP MER X.TRA</CO><MS>FINANCIAL (FIN)TECHNOLOGY (TEC)</MS><IN>AEROSPACE (ARO)BANKRUPTCIES (BCY)DIVERSIFIED FINANCIAL SERVICES, CREDIT INSTITUTIONS (FIS)SECURITIES (SCR)</IN><NS>BANKRUPTCY DECLARATIONS AND PROCEEDINGS (BCY)RESTRUCTURINGS, RECAPITALIZATION (RCN)</NS><RE>NORTH AMERICA (NME)NEW YORK (NY)TEXAS (TX)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   AUSTIN, Texas -- Two investment banking firms that workedon the 1987 leveraged buy-out of Tracor Inc. agreed to pay $4million to settle claims related to the buy-out.   The payment by American Express Co.'s Shearson LehmanBrothers unit and Merrill Lynch andamp; Co., plus $1 million fromTracor, will go to certain creditors of the company, whichsought U.S. bankruptcy-court protection earlier this year.The settlement was reached Friday, a spokeswoman for Tracorsaid. Spokesmen for Shearson and Merrill Lynch weren'tavailable to comment Friday.</LP><TEXT>   Tracor's reorganization under Chapter 11 of the U.S.Bankruptcy Code also was completed Friday with the emergenceof two new companies -- Tracor Inc., a defense concern, andLittelfuse Inc., a maker of commercial electrical parts.   Tracor was purchased in 1987 by Westmark Systems Inc. forabout $714 million in a leveraged buy-out. The company wasn'table to meet optimistic growth projections and filed toreorganize under bankruptcy-court protection in February.</TEXT></DOC>